Math and Logic

Cut Exactly in Half

How can we draw a single line to divide a circle (or group of circles) precisely in half? If we're successful, we should have the same area and circumference on both sides of the line.

With a single circle, we can do this by drawing any line through the center, but what about when we have more circles?

What about two circles touching side by side? The previous strategy works, and we gain a new one as well. We can make a line that passes through the circles' centers, or we can pass a line between the two circles. Either of these will work.

But there's an additional way to think about two circles that includes both of the above and many other values besides. Imagine drawing a rectangle around these two circles and labelling the center of the rectangle. Because any line drawn through the center will divide the two halves of the rectangle symmetrically, it will also divide the circles into two parts with equal area and perimeter.

Another way to describe this is that a line through the two circles' point of tangency will evenly divide their areas and circumferences.

How can these ideas help with the problem below?

Today's Challenge

Is it possible to position the line so that it evenly divides these five circles into two parts of equal area and perimeter?

It is possible. It is not possible.

Correct!

    João Pedro Afonso
    Jun 10, 2020

    This is always possible for a lot of shapes. I'll present here the answer I gave at 2019/09, thinking on a general case:

    Consider an arbitrary drawing limited to certain region. Consider also a straight line with an arbitrary slope that may or may not cutting our figure:

    We know it is always possible to shift that line in a such a way to cut the area of the figure in half, because if we put it at some extreme bottom, the area bellow it is zero, and if we start to shift it up, the area bellow will start to grow until eventually will be all... having pass the point where it was half of the total AT/2A_T/2AT​/2 (green line). Let's call this area, Ab(0º)A_b(0º)Ab​(0º) (bellow, and 0º because I intend to rotate the line later). There will be a correspondent perimeter Pb(0º)P_b(0º)Pb​(0º) on the bellow side of the line and another perimeter Pu(0º)P_u(0º)Pu​(0º) on the other side.

    The main fact to retain is, while we can find a position for the line that divides the area in half, it is not certain this will divide the perimeter in half. Likely, there will be some x different from zero verifying:

    {Pu=PT/2+xPb=PT/2−x\begin{cases}P_u=P_T/2+x\\P_b=P_T/2-x\\ \end{cases}{Pu​=PT​/2+xPb​=PT​/2−x​​

    Now, let's rotate the straight green line some angle around certain arbitrary point:

    Likely, the areas Ab′(α)A_b'(\alpha)Ab′​(α) and Au′(α)A_u'(\alpha)Au′​(α) are not divided equally now, but we can compensate that, shifting the line until they became equal again (green line →\rightarrow→ red line). Again will have perimeters Pu(α)P_u(\alpha)Pu​(α) and Pb(α)P_b(\alpha)Pb​(α), that may or may not be equal. If we do this rotation continuously, it is easy to understand that Pu(α)=PT/2+x(α)P_u(\alpha)=P_T/2+x(\alpha)Pu​(α)=PT​/2+x(α) and Pb(α)=PT/2−x(α)P_b(\alpha)=P_T/2-x(\alpha)Pb​(α)=PT​/2−x(α) are continuous functions in α\alphaα. And now comes the eureka moment: when the rotation is 180º, the line becomes equal to itself again, with sides exchanged:

    Pb(180º)=Pu(0º)P_b(180º)=P_u(0º)Pb​(180º)=Pu​(0º)

    That means Pb(α)P_b(\alpha)Pb​(α) goes continuously from Pb(0º)=PT/2−xP_b(0º)=P_T/2-xPb​(0º)=PT​/2−x, to Pb(180º)=PT/2+xP_b(180º)=P_T/2+xPb​(180º)=PT​/2+x, with a consequence that there must be an angle between 0º and 180º where the perimeter is HALF, PT/2P_T/2PT​/2, because the function must pass there!

    At the time, @Jim Pearson made a pertinent objection about applying this idea to shapes with straight lines, but fortunately, our problem don't have them. By the way, knowing it is possible is not the same as to find the right line. Fortunately, there is a simple way to find it:

    Divide de figure into two sets, each having 180º rotation symmetry around a point of the set... and draw a straight line passing through the points

    If it is possible to do this, this will work because, any straight line through the (let's call it the center) point of a set, will always divide the set in portions with the same area and perimeter, because of the symmetry. The line that cross both points will evenly divide both sets at the same time. This works even if we separate the sets has I did above to show them.

    Note also a fourth solution there. This is more tricky. We can also try to take out an even number of circles and divide the figure again into two sets, each having 180º rotation symmetry around a point of the set... and draw a straight line passing through the points as long the figure divides the circles taken out too (if one single set remains, that will do it, too).

    Thanks for @Arron Kau, @David Vrekken, and many others for showing the way at that time (I was too busy finding a general solution at the time)

    Area greater than perimeter? Comparing these 2 quantities is weird. The question is asking whether each would be divided evenly into 2 parts respectively. Even so, the area and perimeter may not be equal.

    Two conditions must be satisfied:

    1) The area is divided evenly.

    2) The perimeter is divided evenly.

    You can try to find a scenarios where area is divided evenly. Then try to find a scenario where the area is divided evenly and perimeter is greater on one side. Then find one where perimeter is less on the same side while areas are equal. Then there should be something in between where the perimeter and areas is equal on both sides.

    Ken Haley
    Jun 11, 2020

    The question asks if it's possible. Without finding an exact solution we can prove that a solution exists. Simply place the line horizontally anywhere, at any angle below the circles. Slowly move the line upward, as you do the area below the line will slowly increase and the area above the line will slowly decrease. At some point the two areas will be equal.

    Ken Haley
    Jun 13, 2020

    Another solution: Think of this is as 6 circles with the upper right circle missing. Now it's easy to find the exact "center of mass" of these 6 circles; it's the point where the top middle circle touches the bottom middle circle. Call this point A. Next find the center of mass of the missing circle; that's just that circle's center. Call this point B. Join points A and B with a straight line and there's your cut. This has to work because (1) any line through A is bound to divide the areas of the original 6 circles exactly in half. By going through B, we know that deleting that upper right circle, we are subtracting exactly one-half of a circle's area from both sides of the line, since our line goes through the center of that circle. (The diagram of this solution has been shown in other replies here, but not this explanation, I don't think.)

    Here is an interesting but non constructive proof of the existence of such cut. It extends to much more complex shapes than just circles and it uses a bit of algebraic topology.

    Consider the affine forms of R2,(x,y)→a.x+b.y+c\mathbb{R}^2, (x, y) \rightarrow a.x + b.y + cR2,(x,y)→a.x+b.y+c such that ∥(a,b,c)∥2=1\Vert (a, b, c) \Vert_2 = 1∥(a,b,c)∥2​=1. The space of those forms identifies to the sphere S2\mathbb{S}^2S2. Given a form aaa we define the function fff with values in R2\mathbb{R}^2R2 such that f(a)f(a)f(a) is the pair (perimeter, area) contained in the half space {x∈R2∣a(x)≥0}\{x \in \mathbb{R}^2 \mid a(x) \geq 0\}{x∈R2∣a(x)≥0}. f:S2→R2f : \mathbb{S}^2 \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^2f:S2→R2 is continuous, hence with Borsuk-Ulam theorem there exists a form aaa such that f(a)=f(−a)f(a) = f(-a)f(a)=f(−a).

    Since the half plane given by aaa is just the opposite of the one defined by −a-a−a (with respect to the line l={x∈R2∣a(x)=0}l = \{x \in \mathbb{R}^2 \mid a(x) = 0\}l={x∈R2∣a(x)=0}), the perimeter and the area that lies on one side of lll is equal to the one on the other side.

    Adam Buck
    Jun 14, 2020

    Here is an argument inspired by the idea of center of mass.

    If we consider any collection of shapes as solid objects of uniform density, then any line through the center of mass necessarily divides the shapes in half by area.

    Now consider the boundary of the shapes as being wire of uniform density. This object also has a center of mass and any line through this center of mass will divide the perimeters in half.

    The line through these two points is such a line dividing the figure in half by both area and perimeter.

    Always possible via pancake theorem

So take this at some angle, and the split of the circumference will either be even (in which case your done) or not even, and if it isn't even, rotate through 180 degrees, at which point the split will be inverted, so there must be a point where the split is perfectly balanced

    Chris Gray
    Jun 11, 2020

    I don't have a drawing for this as I did it in my head in less than a minute.

    Split the circles up into two rows; top row centre is where the 2 circles touch bottom row is in the centre of the middle of the 3 circles

    Any straight line that passes through the centre of a group of identical circles will divide them into equal parts ie area (& hence perimeter)

    Therefor a line that passes through the centre of the top row and also the centre of the bottom row must divide the 2 rows into equal parts.

    A clever question but much simpler than it may originally appear.

    @David Vreken has the best general solution, which subsume a lot of the others here. Also be sure to see the much more general solution by @João Pedro Afonso.

    ...But I didn't notice the following approach to discovering Vreken's top-right solution among the solutions posted so far:

    Add the "missing" sixth circle in the top-right. Any line through the very center point (the tangency of the middle two circles) will equally split the six circles' area and perimeter. So now we just need to find one that splits the missing circle's area and perimeter. And that's easy, by passing the line through that circle's center.

    Daniel Daniel

    Assume the line is an arrow so that it has a direction and a left and a right side. It is easy to see that it is possible to draw the arrow leaving two circles to its left and three to its right. It is also possible to draw the arrow leaving three circles to its left and two to its right. And it is possible to rotate the arrow continuously from one position to the other. So in this rotation it must go through a position where it has two and a half circles on each side.

    Proving that this equality takes place at the same position in terms of both arc length and segment area is a different matter, though.
